Scaling policies.

An auto scaling group adjusts its capacity through policies, and you often combine them.

The simplest, and the right default, is target tracking: you pick a metric and a target value, say keep average see-pee-you at fifty percent, and AWS adds and removes instances to hold the metric there, managing the alarms and cooldowns for you.

Step scaling is for when the relationship between metric and capacity is non-linear: you define an alarm and then steps, adding more instances the worse the breach gets, so a small overshoot adds one instance and a large one adds four.

Scheduled scaling sets the capacity at specific times, for predictable patterns like business hours or end-of-month batches. And predictive scaling uses machine learning on the last couple of weeks of metrics to forecast load and pre-scale before demand arrives; you pair it with target tracking, letting prediction handle the forecastable bulk and target tracking absorb the rest.

The old simple scaling, one step with a blocking cooldown, is legacy; don't use it for new designs.
